[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1. Semi-Slav Introduction and"]
[Black "Semi-Slav Key Ideas"]
[Result "*"]
[PlyCount "8"]

1. d4 d5 {This is the most common way to play the Semi-Slav Defense.} 2. c4 c6
3. Nf3 {White can also play Nc3 but it will transpose after Nf3 on the next
move.} Nf6 {Black increases his control of the e4-square and supports his pawn
on d5.} 4. Nc3 e6 {This is the starting position of the Semi-Slav Defense.
From here, White has two main options: 5.e3 and 5.Bg5.} *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1. Semi-Slav Introduction and"]
[Black "Common Mistake by Black in th"]
[Result "*"]
[PlyCount "13"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. e3 {This is the most common move in
this position, and we will explore it later in more detail.} Nbd7 {This is
Black's normal development in the Semi-Slav. Black can follow up with Bd6 on
the next move.} 6. Qc2 dxc4 {Taking the pawn on c4 is an important idea in
this variation, but Black has played it prematurely. White can recapture the
pawn in one move with 7.Bxc4 instead of having to move his bishop twice.} 7.
Bxc4 {White has a nice advantage.} *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1. Semi-Slav Introduction and"]
[Black "Another Common Mistake by Bla"]
[Result "*"]
[PlyCount "25"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. e3 Nbd7 6. Qc2 {We reach the same
position as we did in the previous variation.} Bd6 {This is the correct move.
It develops a piece, prepares to castle, and waits for White to move his
light-squared bishop before chopping on c4.} 7. Bd3 {This is the main move,
but White has many other options.} O-O 8. O-O e5 {This early pawn break does
not work out well for Black. Better is the thematic dxc4.} 9. cxd5 {This is
the beginning of a powerful sequence of moves that leaves White with a clear
advantage.} cxd5 {Nxd5 instead hangs the pawn on h7. If Black chooses the move
exd4 instead, White can play exd4 cxd5 Bg5 and White has overwhelming threats
of taking on h7 and/or playing Nb5.} 10. e4 {This move is key.} exd4 {If Black
plays dxe4 instead, he will later have to waste a tempo playing h6 to stop the
threat of Bxh7+. White could simply recapture the pawn with Nxd4 and has very
fluid development for both his pieces and his rooks.} 11. Nxd5 Nxd5 12. exd5 h6
{Black has to stop the threat of Bxh7+} 13. Nxd4 {White has won a pawn but the
pawn on d5 is weak and will likely be lost. However, White has very easy
development and a nice advantage.} *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2. Meran Variation"]
[Black "Meran Variation Introduction"]
[Result "*"]
[PlyCount "14"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. e3 {White is avoiding sharper lines
that can ensue after 5.Bg5 by playing this move. It is also the most common
move in the position as 1.d4 players often prefer quieter play.} Nbd7 6. Bd3 {
This is known as the Meran Variation. White immediately develops his bishop
and prepares to castle.} dxc4 {This is a thematic move. Black makes the bishop
move twice.} 7. Bxc4 b5 {This is the thematic follow-up. Black wins a tempo on
the bishop and prepares to develop his bishop to b7. Now White has a few
different options, but Black gets excellent play in every single one of them!}
*

