1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. e3 Nbd7 6. Qc2 Bd6 7. g4 {This is
known as the Shabalov Attack. The idea is that if Black takes on g4, White
will have excellent attacking chances along the g-file.} dxc4 {This is a good
way of dealing with it.} 8. Bxc4 {White decides to take on c4 immediately.} e5
9. g5 {Now White can attack the knight.} Nd5 {Black always has the d5-square
for his knight as is thematic in this line. The reason White cannot win a pawn
by taking twice on d5 is that Black can play Qa5+!, winning a piece.} 10. Bd2
exd4 {Black has a good position.} *

