1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. cxd5 {This is the most popular
sideline and is often used as a drawing weapon.} exd5 {Black frees his bishop.}
6. Qc2 g6 {This is my favorite move to play for a win. Black wants to
fianchetto his kingside bishop.} 7. Bg5 Be7 8. e4 dxe4 9. Bxf6 {White has to
give up the bishop pair if he wants to take back on e4.} Bxf6 10. Qxe4+ Kf8 {
The king can run happily to the g7-square where it is very safe.} 11. Bc4 Kg7
12. O-O Re8 {A logical move.} 13. Qf4 Be6 {Black challenges White's bishop.}
14. Bxe6 Rxe6 15. Rfe1 Qd6 {Black seems to have the slightly more comfortable
endgame after a set of trades because he can play against White's isolated
d4-pawn.} *

